From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: Operating System Virus Checking (PC)

>From:    ampex!russest@decwrl.dec.com (Steve Russell)

First, I have to take exception with the subject. The real question is
Integrity Management by OSs, Virus protection is just one result.

>The problem is, virus protection will only be good for the first three
>or four hours of the o/s release. After that, the hackers will have
>started passing out new virii just for that o/s.

Not if done properly. First all previously existing viruses would become
obsolete if implimented properly (validation of .COM files is the only
sticky point). This alone would be a great help.

Next, with the same caveat, all techniques used by current viruses would
become obsolete so the present cloning practise would stop (Michelangelo
is really a clone of STONED).

Also, while new techniques would be possible, they would require much more
effort and code. A 100 byte virus would not be possible anymore with the
result that many hiding places would go away and it would take much more
programming effort on the part of virus writers (why there have not been
any widespread mainframe viruses).

Finally, we could eliminate a whole class of virus - those accounting for
more than half of all reported infections and including Mich again - and
be reasonably sure that when DOS loads, the system is clean.

IMHO there is no longer any excuse for there being NO checking from the
OS.

>The same argument could be made on why don't o/s writers use some form of
>compression scheme on there executibles?

DR-DOS 6.0 does and I have seen reports that MS-DOS 5.1 and IBM OS/2.1 will
also. Just keep asking.
