Date:    Fri, 06 Mar 92 13:40:00 -0400
From:    Al Woodhull <AWOODHULL@hamp.hampshire.edu>
Subject: How much memory in a PC? (PC)

There were a couple of questions in the most recent (v5 n48) Virus-l
bulletin about the total memory seen when using CHKDSK. A little
explanation might help:

In the old days when the IBM PC first came out some were sold with as
little as 64K of memory installed. Part of the self-test that occurs
when you apply power is a determination of exactly how much memory  is
in your PC. The number is saved in memory and can be accessed by any
program (or the operating system). Thus a program that runs in a small
amount of memory can use additional memory, if available, if its
performance can be improved by doing so. A program that needs a large
amount of memory can be prevented from running at all if the needed
memory isn't available; that's nicer than crashing.

The number can also be modified. On an XT clone I use the ROM BIOS
modifies this number, effectively telling the operating system and any
program  I run that my computer has only 638K, not 640K. The BIOS uses
that 2K for something, I'm not sure what. If I had only 512K installed
in my computer the BIOS would still take that 2K and leave 510K
available. Apparently some PS/2 machines do something similar.

Any program that wants to permanently take some memory out of use can
modify this number. That's what Michelangelo and some other viruses do.
They then use that upper 1 or 2K themselves. Their resident portion
will never be overwritten in the normal course of things because the
operating system is told there is no memory there. But it's not just
viruses that use this trick.

If you run CHKDSK and find you don't have a full 640K you don't
necessarily have a virus.  You must know what number is normally
reported for the size of memory when your system is clean. It might be
less than 640K to begin with.

