Date:    Fri, 06 Mar 92 13:52:35 -0500
From:    Kevin_Haney@NIHCR31.BITNET
Subject: Antiviral features in operating systems

Steve Russell, in response to my view that antiviral and integrity-
checking features should be built into PC operating systems, writes

 >The problem is, virus protection will only be good for the first three
 >or four hours of the o/s release. After that, the hackers will have
 >started passing out new virii just for that o/s. What you're asking is
 >just not practical for the o/s developer. Not enough time or money on
 >a losing proposition. The same argument could be made on why don't o/s
 >writers use some form of compression scheme on there executibles?

Unfortunately, however, he didn't quote my response to that argument
which was that...

        "Of course, someone would eventually write a virus to subvert
        such protection, but 95% of virus damage is caused by the 10
        most common viruses today, e.g., Stoned, Jerusalem, Joshi.
        Protection against 95% of viruses is better than protection
        against 0%."

I still think this is a valid argument.  I did not mean to imply that
operating system manufacturers should have to make an OS 100% secure
against viruses.  Rather, they should make it secure against the
current crop of common viruses that cause almost all of the damage.
As Padgett has said, protection from almost all boot sector viruses
could be accomplished in a few dozen bytes of code so there would be
no investment of time or money.

The question of why OS writers don't use compression schemes is not in
fact analagous because taking up less disk space is just a nice feature,
but being totally unsecured against a virus attack damages the trust
that users should be able feel in their operating system. (By the way,
a compression scheme is in fact slated to be included in a update of
OS/2 2.0.)  A truly analagous (invalid) argument to the one Mr. Russell
makes would be that car manufacturers shouldn't build door locks into
cars because someone would just invent a pick to break the lock.  I hope
the flaw is apparant in both cases.

